Author::::lollipopshoes
DateTime::::2016-03-07T04:38:38Z
Paul, your original comment puts 'global' in inverted commas, which seems to suggest that you doubt whether it can genuinely be described as such. While you are plausibly right to be skeptical about this, I suspect that it is not for the right reasons, (otherwise, you would have your answers by now). There is a huge field concerned with global SURFACE temperatures, which is to do with how you amass all of the thermometers in the world to say something sensible about the global average surface temperature (the one humans care about). It's hard, because the system wasn't really designed to answer this question when it first began decades and centuries ago, and because humans themselves change the climate of cities, etc. Your comments have a tone that scientists are engaged with hiding the location of said sensors, and while this simply isn't the case, it's quite hard to visualize the whole network because it's so large, and because it is non-stationary in time. 



